This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with image deconvolution, which is a common problem in computer vision. Additionally, the use of deep learning techniques such as neural nets suggests that it may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The use of priors in the model also suggests that it may belong to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the experimental evaluation of the model's performance on standard benchmark datasets suggests that it may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
